    "summary": "The Young Turk Revolution of July 1908 restored the Ottoman constitution of 1876 and ended the autocratic rule of Sultan Abdulhamid II. The revolution was carried out by the Committee of Union and Progress (CUP), a reform-minded nationalist organization whose members had been organizing in exile and within the Ottoman military. Military units in Macedonia mutinied and marched toward Istanbul, and the sultan capitulated rather than face civil war.\n\nThe revolution initially raised hopes for a constitutional, multiethnic Ottoman state, and was celebrated by communities across the empire. However, the CUP increasingly moved toward Turkish nationalism and centralized control, particularly after a counter-revolution in 1909 that they suppressed violently. The CUP's dominance led directly to the conditions in which the [[event:2753|Armenian Genocide]] was organized during World War I. The Young Turk period also saw the empire lose most of its remaining European territories in the [[event:3444|Balkan Wars]], accelerating both the decline of the Ottoman state and the radicalization of its nationalist leadership.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Young_Turk_Revolution",
